//! `:wat::kernel::StdOutService` — substrate runtime service that
//! owns fd 1 (or a test-supplied output fd), receives typed
//! [`holon::HolonAST`] values from per-thread message-pipes, serializes
//! each to line-delimited EDN via [`wat_edn::write`], and writes the
//! bytes to its output fd. A producer-side ack channel signals
//! completion of each individual write (mini-TCP discipline; arc 089
//! slice 5 + `wat/console.wat`).
//!
//! # Pattern (inherited from slice 1f-i; reused by 1f-iii)
//!
//! - **Singleton boot:** [`start_stdout_service`] is idempotent; first
//!   call spawns the worker thread; subsequent calls return the same
//!   `&'static` handle. Wired into wat-cli boot in slice 1f-iv.
//! - **Test spawn:** [`StdOutService::spawn_for_test`] returns a
//!   fresh, non-singleton handle writing to a caller-supplied
//!   `RawFd`. The static fd 1 belongs to the singleton; tests use
//!   their own pipe ends so multiple cargo-test processes don't
//!   contend over the host's real fd 1 and so each test is hermetic.
//! - **Per-thread registration:** producers call
//!   [`StdOutServiceHandle::register`] with their `ThreadId`; the
//!   service stores a [`crossbeam_channel::Receiver`] for that
//!   thread and returns the matching [`Sender`] so the thread can
//!   feed `(Arc<HolonAST>, AckSender)` pairs. Calling
//!   [`StdOutServiceHandle::unregister`] drops the stored Receiver.
//!
//! # Send-with-ack contract
//!
//! Each message a producer thread sends is a tuple
//! `(Arc<HolonAST>, AckSender)`. The service:
//!
//! 1. Serializes the HolonAST to wire-format EDN bytes (terminated
//!    with `\n`)
//! 2. `libc::write`s the bytes to the output fd
//! 3. Sends `()` on the AckSender to unblock the producer
//!
//! The AckSender is one-shot — `crossbeam_channel::bounded(1)` —
//! created by the producer per send. A producer that wants to know
//! its write reached the kernel buffer blocks on the AckReceiver
//! after sending. This is the mini-TCP discipline: every message has
//! a per-message acknowledgement; per-thread message ordering is
//! preserved (a single Sender + FIFO crossbeam channel); cross-thread
//! ordering is NOT guaranteed (Select picks readiness across threads;
//! producers race for the worker).
//!
//! # Internal shape — crossbeam Select multiplex
//!
//! UNLIKE slice 1f-i (which uses `libc::poll` on `(input_fd,
//! self_pipe_read_fd)`), the worker here multiplexes via
//! [`crossbeam_channel::Select`] over:
//!
//! - The control channel ([`ControlMsg`] carrier — Register /
//!   Unregister / Shutdown)
//! - N per-thread data channels (one Receiver per registered thread)
//!
//! `Select::select_timeout` blocks until any channel is ready. On
//! readiness:
//!
//! - **Control fired:** drain via `try_recv`; mutate the registry
//!   (add Receiver / drop Receiver / set shutdown flag); rebuild the
//!   Select set on the next iteration.
//! - **Data fired:** receive `(Arc<HolonAST>, AckSender)`; serialize;
//!   write to output_fd; signal ack.
//!
//! The Select set is rebuilt on every loop iteration. This is O(N)
//! per iteration where N is the number of registered threads — bounded
//! by the spawn-thread pool size, typically small. Honest delta:
//! crossbeam's `Select` doesn't expose an "add receiver mid-block"
//! primitive; rebuilding each iteration is the established crossbeam
//! idiom for dynamic registration. See SCORE-SLICE-1F-II for the
//! design rationale.
//!
//! # Single-writer guard on fd 1
//!
//! ONLY the service worker thread calls `libc::write` on the output
//! fd. Producer threads always send through their per-thread channel
//! and let the worker do the syscall. This is the doctrine that
//! prevents interleaved writes — concurrent producers can't tear each
//! other's lines because each line completes inside the worker's
//! single-threaded write loop before the next is processed.
//!
//! The public API doesn't expose direct fd access; the only way to
//! reach the output fd from outside the service is via `register` →
//! send pair. Verified by inspection.
//!
//! # Shutdown semantics
//!
//! On [`ControlMsg::Shutdown`] (sent by [`StdOutServiceHandle::Drop`]
//! for test handles), the worker DRAINS all pending per-thread
//! messages before exiting. Each drained message is serialized,
//! written, and acked normally — producers don't lose data. After
//! the drain, the worker exits and its stored Senders/Receivers
//! drop, signalling disconnect to any producer that didn't ack
//! before shutdown. This choice mirrors `stdin`'s
//! `notify_eof_and_drop`: shutdown is a clean drain, not an abort.
//!
//! # Pattern reuse for slice 1f-iii (StdErrService)
//!
//! Slice 1f-iii applies the same shape to fd 2 with two variations:
//!
//! - **First-panic-wins:** the StdErrService's data payload is a
//!   panic-cascade event (not arbitrary HolonAST). Once one panic
